         <p>The service proceeded without hitch, and everything was satisfactory save the clamorous music for 'O Salutaris Hostia".  <hi rend="bold underline">The Abp. gave me quite a monition about it afterwards</hi>. Both the new bishops - <persName xml:id="178">Kensington</persName> &amp; <persName xml:id="72">Barking</persName> - lunched with me afterwards, as did also the Bps of S. Alban's &amp; Colchester, <persName xml:id="179">Sir John Hanham</persName>,<persName xml:id="180">M<hi rend="superscript underline">r</hi> &amp; M<hi rend="superscript underline">rs</hi> D. Howard</persName>, <persName xml:id="181">M<hi rend="superscript underline">rs</hi> Johnson</persName>, <persName xml:id="182">Miss Festing</persName>, Miss Barney, <persName xml:id="98">M<hi rend="superscript underline">r</hi></persName> &amp; <persName xml:id="616">M<hi rend="superscript underline">rs</hi> Hunt</persName>, <persName xml:id="184">M<hi rend="superscript underline">r</hi> Montague Smith</persName>, <persName xml:id="62">Kirshbaum</persName>, <persName xml:id="170">Perkins</persName>, <persName xml:id="78">Bedford</persName>, <persName xml:id="185">Du Cane</persName>.</p>
         <p>
<hi rend="bold">[18]</hi>
         </p>
         <p>The Bp. of S. Alban's told me as a great secret - tho', I suspect, everybody knows it â€“ that <persName xml:id="36">Lord Salisbury</persName> has given &#x00A3;<hi rend="underline">5000</hi> as an endowment for the new Suffragan.  This with the archdeaconry &amp; the <orgName xml:id="9">Hospital</orgName> will provide an income of &#x00A3;1000 per ann:</p>
         <p>
<hi rend="bold">[19]</hi>
         </p><div type="letter">
         <p>18<hi rend="superscript underline">th</hi> Feb:1901.</p>
         <p>Dear Sir,</p>
         <p>Re. <persName xml:id="1556" display="no">M<hi rend="superscript underline">r</hi> James Smith</persName></p>
         <p>30 Parker St:</p>
         <p>I am obliged to you for your letter of the 15<hi rend="superscript underline">th</hi> inst: in wh. you suggest that a pension of 16/- weekly sh<hi rend="superscript underline">d</hi> be raised for M<hi rend="superscript underline">r</hi> Smith.  You are, of course, aware that there is no fund at my disposal wh. can be charged permanently with any contribution towards such an expenditure.  My action c<hi rend="superscript underline">d</hi> in no way pledge my successor.  I am, however, prepared to pay out of the alms entrusted to me for the relief of the poor, a contribution of 7/- weekly, provided you can raise the other 9/- - such contribution to cease when M<hi rend="superscript underline">r</hi> Smith's <persName xml:id="1557" display="no">eldest child</persName> reaches the age of sixteen years, when the case must be reconsidered on its merits.  Also, I repeat, this is a personal undertaking, which w<hi rend="superscript underline">d</hi>  - ipso facto expire if I left the parish.  I suggest that I sh<hi rend="superscript underline">d</hi> pay over to the <orgName xml:id="138">C.O.S.</orgName> a quarterly sum of &#x00A3;4.11.0. to be distributed by the C<hi rend="superscript underline">tee</hi> in weekly payments to M<hi rend="superscript underline">r</hi> Smith.</p>
         <p>	Believe me, faithfully yrs,</p>
         <p>		H. HENSLEY HENSON</p></div>
         <p><persName xml:id="186">Captain J. Gaspard Le Marchant</persName>.</p>
